{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WxNN3PrDF3UNtZq8mvFeHm","type":"tool_result","content":"   140→> - `codeharness progress --clear` ONCE per story, not twice\n   141→> - Timestamps: use the current time from your system prompt, don't shell out to `date`\n   142→> - Don't re-read files that haven't changed since last read\n   143→\n   144→**Live progress updates:** Before executing each sub-step (3a/3b/3c/3d), update sprint-state.json with the current progress:\n   145→\n   146→```bash\n   147→codeharness progress --story {story_key} --phase {create|dev|review|verify} --action \"Starting {step description}\"\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→This enables external tools to see what the session is doing in real time.\n   151→\n   152→### 3a: If status is `backlog` — Run Create Story\n   153→\n   154→Invoke the create-story workflow via Agent tool to generate the story file:\n   155→\n   156→```\n   157→Use the Agent tool with:\n   158→  prompt: \"Run /create-story for story {story_key}. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n   159→\n   160→**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n   161→- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n   162→- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n   163→- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n   164→- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n   165→\n   166→Default to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   167→\n   168→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   169→- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n   170→- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n   171→- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n   172→- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\n   173→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   174→\n   175→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   176→- Total tool calls: N\n   177→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   178→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   179→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   180→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   181→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   182→```\n   183→\n   184→After the Agent completes:\n   185→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   186→2. Verify the story status changed from `backlog` to `ready-for-dev`\n   187→3. If status didn't change, increment attempts and retry this step (up to max_attempts)\n   188→4. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: backlog → ready-for-dev`\n   189→\n   190→### 3b: If status is `ready-for-dev` or `in-progress` — Run Dev Story\n   191→\n   192→**Pre-check: Verification findings.** Before invoking dev-story, read the story file at `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md` and check if it contains a `## Verification Findings` section. If it does, extract the full content of that section (everything from `## Verification Findings` until the next `##` heading or end of file). Store this as `verification_findings_text`.\n   193→\n   194→Invoke the dev-story workflow via Agent tool to implement the story:\n   195→\n   196→```\n   197→Use the Agent tool with:\n   198→  prompt: \"Run /bmad-dev-story for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md — implement all tasks, write tests, and mark the story for review. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously through all tasks until complete. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   199→\n   200→{IF verification_findings_text is not empty, include this block:}\n   201→IMPORTANT — VERIFICATION FINDINGS FROM PREVIOUS CYCLE:\n   202→The following ACs failed verification. Fix the code to make them pass:\n   203→\n   204→{verification_findings_text}\n   205→\n   206→Read the findings carefully. Each failing AC includes the error output from the verifier. Your job is to fix the underlying code so these ACs pass on the next verification run. Do NOT remove the ## Verification Findings section from the story file — it stays for reference.\n   207→{END IF block}\n   208→\n   209→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   210→- Problems encountered (build failures, test failures, unclear task specs, missing APIs)\n   211→- Workarounds applied (anything hacky, copied patterns that felt wrong, TODOs left behind)\n   212→- Code quality concerns (areas that need refactoring, edge cases not handled, tech debt added)\n   213→- Observations (unexpected complexity, architectural mismatches, dependency issues)\n   214→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   215→\n   216→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   217→- Total tool calls: N\n   218→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   219→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   220→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   221→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   222→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   223→```\n   224→\n   225→After the Agent completes:\n   226→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   227→2. Verify the story status changed to `review`\n   228→3. If status is still `in-progress` or `ready-for-dev`, this may indicate failure — increment attempts\n   229→4. If attempts >= max_attempts, go to Step 6 (failure handling)\n   230→5. If status didn't reach `review`, retry this step\n   231→6. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: → review`\n   232→\n   233→### 3c: If status is `review` — Run Code Review\n   234→\n   235→Invoke the code-review workflow via Agent tool:\n   236→\n   237→```\n   238→Use the Agent tool with:\n   239→  prompt: \"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01BtwRQiK3Prp7HpVyRuHgiq","session_id":"caf97759-8abf-4687-a81a-d927d13354ea","uuid":"309c100b-35f7-4627-9055-3d9c1ba7a550","timestamp":"2026-03-27T13:03:27.642Z"}
